, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","Church of St. Mary, Stoke d' Abernon, Surrey, England":"Stoke D'Abernon, Surrey, England","Europe":"Europe","Stoke D'Abernon, Surrey, England":"Stoke D'abernon, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Croyser","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of <b>Croser</b>, itself a variant of   Crozier  .","In some cases possibly also an altered form of German   Grosser  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Crozier","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name for one who carried a cross or a bishop's crook or pastoral staff in ecclesiastical processions, from Middle English <i>crosier</i> (Old French <i>crosier, crocier, crosser</i>). It may also denoted a seller of crosses or, as a topographic name, a dweller by a cross (compare 2 below).","French: topographic name for a dweller by a cross or crossroad, an agent derivative of <i>croix</i> ‘cross’ (from Latin <i>crux</i>), or a habitational name from Le Crozier in Rhône-Alpes, a placename of the same etymology."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":8,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hu